Part I

  1. Graph A has the highest F ratio because the slope is the largest, meaning there is a greater correlation than if the slope smaller/ closer to the base mean (showing a more linear relationship than the other two). We can tell by looking at the graph that the F is larger because the model improvement in prediction is observably larger than the difference between the model and the observed data by a much larger margin than can be seen in either B or C.

  2. The main difference between correlation and regression is that correlation determines the relationship between two variables, “x” and “y”, while regression is the prediction of a dependent variable value given the known value of the independent variable. Correlation observes the relationship between the two variables as a whole, while regression is the numerical prediction of how one variable influences the other. Correlation is used to determine a correlation while regression focuses on a line of best fit between by one variable on the basis of another. Regression is based on predicting causality while correlation does not (it seeks to show correlation). Correlation is also reversable, meaning if you were to switch “x” and “y” you would get the same results as that is not the case with regression. When it comes to statistics they use (Pearson’s r and the beta coefficient) correlation uses Pearson’s R while regression uses the beta coefficient. Even though when computed, both Pearson’s r and the beta coefficient may look similar they measure different things. The Pearson’s r is as statistic used to measure the relationship between two variables and the way the two correlate (a value between -1 and 1). To get r you are essentially looking at the way “x” and “y” covary with each other (correlation of the product of the covariance of “x” and “y” together) divided by the product of the standard deviation of “x” and the standard deviation of “y”. In other words, this equation gives you an idea of how the variables correlate as a whole. Regression and the use of beta is a bit different. Regression’s use of beta is to look at the way one data point is predicted on the other. Beta is calculated by determining the covariance (the way the two variables both differ from their respective means) of x and y divided by the variance of x. This equation determines the slope of the line of best fit and you can use this number to arrive at a specific x intercept on that line. With correlation and r, you can find your t statistic.

  1. Charts A, B and C each show the deviations of 10 data points from their respective means.
  1. B and C are correlated
  2. B is a positive correlation while C is a negative correlation
  3. For Graph B you can tell that the data is positively correlated because for every point of x that goes up, the point of y goes up and in the same manner. Meaning each point has a relatively similar deviation from their respective means (e.g. When X goes up 1 unit from its mean, Y goes up 1 unit for its mean). For graph C you can tell they are negatively correlated because for every point of x that goes down, y goes up, and vice versa. Each point seems to react in opposition of the other and like in graph B each point deviates from its respective mean in similar ways.
  4. Graph A would represent uncorrelated data.
  5. They would appear uncorrelated because neither point of x has a relationship to y, meaning that if x goes up y might or might not go up, there is no observable pattern between the data points. In addition, each data point of x deviates from its means much differently than each data point of y on its own respective mean, unlike what we saw in graphs B and C.

  2. This is not significant because the confidence interval crosses zero. If a confidence interval crosses zero, then the confidence interval includes zero (null value). It also means that if the study were repeated the value could be positive or negative when in reality, we want one or the other, not both.
  3. You are reviewing data in order to summarize the evidence for the association between a measure of psychopathy and ability to recognize fearful facial expressions. Below are the correlations from five studies:
  1. My overall interpretation of this data is that whenever there is a significant result found, there appears to be a small (but still significant, and pretty moderate for psychology since .3 is usual) negative correlation (effect) between psychopathy and ability to recognize fearful faces. For the nonsignificant studies the confidence interval crosses zero, further confirming non significance. I want to say there appears to be an association with significant studies however almost half (40%) of the studies show insignificant results. This tells me that before I can confirm an association, more studies need to be done. It is worth noting that those studies that were insignificant did have small sample sizes, which signals to me that they might have thought they would find a large effect, which in reality, they failed to do. I would recommend going back to the drawing board and attempting more studies, and then if more significant results with larger sample sizes are found, explain the issue with the other two studies.
  2. Overall, I would give more weight to the significant studies because the sample size is much larger. The studies with the small sample size makes me wonder how large they thought the effect size would be and how grossly undercalculated it was. If it was a psychopathy/no psychopathy design the study barely has enough to satisfy the “minimum” of 20 per cell. There could be a number of reasons other than under powering their study (e.g.dropouts) that could have resulted in small sample size. Even with that being said, regardless of lent weight to the studies with the higher sample sizes, they should run a few more.
  3. I would conclude that even though I would weigh the significant studies more because of sample size, there is not enough information to determine an association just yet. I would like to see more studies with higher sample sizes as well as how large they are hoping their effect size to be as well as a power analysis to determine that the two significant studies were in fact under powered which would help them explain the issue given more significant findings. *I would also like to point out that if the sample sizes were all similar and half the results were still insignificant, my reccommendation might not be the same (run more studies) in fear of P-hacking.
  1. Spearman’s rho would give a better summary of the data because the data is ranked so the variation between the data is reduced. This would be especially the case if ordinal variables were used.

data <- data.frame(state.x77)

State.x77

matrix with 50 rows and 8 columns giving the following statistics in the respective columns.

Variable Variable Description
Population Population estimate as of July 1, 1975
Income Per capita income (1974)
Illiteracy Illiteracy (1970, percent of population)
Life Exp Life expectancy in years (1969–71)
Murder murder and non-negligent manslaughter rate per 100,000 population (1976)
HS Grad Percent high-school graduates (1970)
Frost mean number of days with minimum temperature below freezing (1931–1960) in capital or large city
Area Land area in square miles

Source

U.S. Department of Commerce, Bureau of the Census (1977) Statistical Abstract of the United States.

U.S. Department of Commerce, Bureau of the Census (1977) County and City Data Book.

References

Becker, R. A., Chambers, J. M. and Wilks, A. R. (1988) The New S Language. Wadsworth & Brooks/Cole.
